{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01LLLE5KL5YsjxDYoPx6biSM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate exactly 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me understand the requirements:\n\n1. File naming: `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.18.txt`\n   - Must use SPACES, not hyphens or underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Filename title must match main title in content (case-insensitive OK)\n\n2. Recipe mix: ~60% English, ~40% Polish\n   - Variety of categories (soups, mains, desserts, salads, appetizers, breads, drinks, preserves)\n   - Mix of multi-word (2-5 words) and single-word titles\n\n3. Avoid these existing recipes (there's a very long list provided)\n\n4. Pattern requirements:\n   - 4 files with SPLIT_TITLE: Title split across 2-4 lines\n   - 4 files with METADATA_PREFIX: Category/serving info before title\n   - 2 files with OCR_CORRUPTION: Misrecognized characters\n\n5. File length: 15-60 lines\n\nLet me plan 10 new recipes that don't exist in the list:\n- Need to think of new recipes not in the provided list\n- Mix of English and Polish\n- Different categories\n\nEnglish recipes I can create:\n1. Tuscan White Bean Dip (not in list - \"Tuscan Bean Soup\" is there but this is different)\n2. Roasted Garlic Parmesan Potatoes\n3. Chocolate Hazelnut Spread\n4. Herb Crusted Lamb Chops\n5. Beet and Orange Salad\n6. Vanilla Custard Tart\n7. Smoked Salmon Dip\n8. Pumpkin Bread\n\nPolish recipes I can create:\n1. Żurawiny z Orzechami (Cranberry Walnut)\n\n\n2. Placki Serowe (Cheese Pancakes)\n3. Piernik z Miodem (Gingerbread with Honey)\n4. Duszona Kapusta ze Słoniną (Braised Cabbage with Bacon)\n5. Zupa Fasolowa (Bean Soup)\n6. Kluski Łyczkowe (Spooned Dumplings)\n7. Marmolada Porzeczkowa (Currant Jam)\n\nNow I'll select 10 recipes maintaining the 60/40 English-Polish split: 6 English and 4 Polish. I need to distribute the pattern types across these selections—4 with split titles, 4 with metadata prefixes, and 2 with OCR corruption.\n\n1. Tuscan White Bean Dip (ENGLISH) - SPLIT_TITLE\n2. Roasted Garlic Parmesan Potatoes (ENGLISH) - METADATA_PREFIX\n3. Chocolate Hazelnut Spread (ENGLISH) - OCR_CORRUPTION\n4. Herb Crusted Lamb Chops (ENGLISH) - SPLIT_TITLE\n5. Beet and Orange Salad (ENGLISH) - METADATA_PREFIX\n6. Smoked Salmon Dip (ENGLISH) - OCR_CORRUPTION\n7. Żurawiny z Orzechami (POLISH) - SPLIT_TITLE\n8. Placki Serowe (POLISH) - METADATA_PREFIX\n9. Piernik z Miodem (POLISH) - SPLIT_TITLE\n10. Marmolada Porzeczkowa (POLISH) - METADATA_PREFIX\n\nChecking the distribution: I have 4 split titles, 4 metadata prefixes, but only 2 OCR corruptions when I need exactly 4 files total with specific pattern requirements. Smoked Salmon Dip (OCR_CORRUPTION) - English. Now I have the complete list of 10 recipes distributed across the three corruption patterns. I'll proceed to generate the files, starting with realistic OCR text that demonstrates each pattern type. For the SPLIT_TITLE files, I'll break titles across multiple lines. For METADATA_PREFIX files, I'll prepend category and meal type information before the actual content. For OCR_CORRUPTION files, I'll introduce character substitutions and scanning artifacts that make the text harder to parse. Z MIODEM\n\nFile 10: Marmolada Porzeczkowa (METADATA_PREFIX)\nPrzetwory | Lato\nMARMOLADA PORZECZKOWA\n\nNow I need to generate realistic OCR content for each file, varying the length between 15-60 lines depending on the recipe type. I should also verify that each filename's title matches exactly with the main title appearing in the text content, allowing for case-insensitive variations. This means \"Tuscan White Bean Dip.generated.18.txt\" must contain \"Tuscan White Bean Dip\" as its primary title, \"Roasted Garlic Parmesan Potatoes.generated.18.txt\" must have \"Roasted Garlic Parmesan Potatoes,\" and so on for all ten files.","signature":""}],"stop_rea